(3392, 228, 'accordion_section_1_accordion_title', 'Planting Vegetated Buffers & Grassy Headlands'),
(3393, 228, '_accordion_section_1_accordion_title', 'field_53976c732daf9'),
(3394, 228, 'accordion_section_1_accordion_content', 'To prevent erosion and promote water filtration vegetation should be present along riparian areas. In some places it may not be possible to keep woody vegetation such as trees or bushes, for example the borders of field crops adjacent to waterways. Grassy strips or headlands are intended for filtration and a setback is an area of land that is left “untouched”. Together these areas are called “Vegetated Buffers”. A setback can be incorporated into the vegetated buffer.\r\n\r\nKeeping soil covered by some grass will have multiple benefits for both biodiversity and the farm. Grass will help to reduce erosion as the root mass help to maintain the soil. Helping soil biodiversity will help to improve soil quality through the preservation of soil nutrients and soil structure. Grasses will also act as a filter, helping to reduce the amount of loose soil or suspended inputs such as pesticides or fertilizers washed into neighbouring waterways.\r\n\r\n<strong>Grassy strips</strong> or headlands are intended for filtration and a <strong>setback</strong> is an area of land that is left “untouched”. Together these areas form “Vegetated Buffers”. A setback can be incorporated into the vegetated buffer. For more information about both setbacks and grassy strips can be found below.'),
