(247, 1, '2014-06-16 19:19:56', '2014-06-16 19:19:56', '<b>Designated Crossing Areas</b>\r\n\r\nWhen livestock or farm equipment travel through watercourses, it can have a negative impact on the water quality downstream, as well as seriously erode the streambanks. By limiting crossing areas to only designated areas (i.e. fencing livestock out of the rest of the water course) it is possible to reduce these impacts.\r\n\r\nBuilding a crossing point that is less susceptible to erosion is another option. This could be achieved through the building of a bridge, or by building a crossing area that is built up to withstand the weight of equipment traffic<span style="color: #ff0000;">. MORE INSTRUCTIONS TO COME.</span>\r\n\r\nIt should be noted, however, that <b>ANY</b> alteration to a stream or watercourse, <b>including bridges</b>, does require permission through the navigable waters act (1985). More information, as well as the appropriate paperwork, can be found <strong><a href="https://www.novascotia.ca/snsmr/paal/nse/paal181.asp">here</a></strong>.', 'Water Crossing', '', 'publish', 'closed', 'closed', '', 'water-crossing-2', '', '', '2014-06-17 14:10:20', '2014-06-17 14:10:20', '', 184, 'http://localhost/farming/?page_id=247', 0, 'page', '', 0),
